%% Graph 2: AI Tools — Ease of Use vs. Enterprise Readiness
%% X-axis: Ease of Use = full workflow ease (setup + sharing + integration + maintenance)
%%          NOT just "easy to start" — reflects real-world friction to get to a useful, connected, shared result
%% Y-axis: Enterprise Readiness = governed, shareable, compliant, auditable
%%
%% Key insight: Copilot M365 and Copilot Studio move LEFT because
%%   - sharing agents is clunky
%%   - connecting to external data requires admin rights
%%   - documentation is perpetually outdated
%%   - full workflow ease is low despite a simple entry experience
%%
%% The "Translation Layer" (top-right) is the target model — not a single product,
%%   but the pattern where a frontend engineer wraps pioneer workflows into governed, accessible tooling.

quadrantChart
    title AI Tools: Ease of Use vs. Enterprise Readiness
    x-axis "Requires Expertise" --> "Accessible to All Employees"
    y-axis "Individual · Ungoverned" --> "Governed · Shareable · Compliant"
    quadrant-1 Enterprise Zone
    quadrant-2 Controlled but Complex
    quadrant-3 Pioneer Zone
    quadrant-4 Easy but Risky

    OpenCode: [0.08, 0.10]
    Claude Code: [0.13, 0.18]
    Claude Desktop / Hermes: [0.18, 0.12]
    ChatGPT Enterprise: [0.52, 0.48]
    Dust: [0.58, 0.62]
    Copilot Studio: [0.30, 0.72]
    Microsoft Copilot M365: [0.35, 0.82]
    Translation Layer ✦: [0.85, 0.88]
